    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="470"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d470">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.48/2740: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-20">December 20,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received December 22—2:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2281. <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi> for December 20th cites a statement by Edward
                        Carter<note n="44" xml:id="d470fn44">Edward C. Carter was president of the
                        American Society for Russian Relief, Inc. (formerly Russian War Relief,
                        Inc.), New York, N.Y.</note> to the effect that during 1944 Russian War
                    Relief intends to send supplies valued at 21 million dollars to the Soviet Union
                    against a value of 16 million dollars this year.<note n="45" xml:id="d470fn45">A
                        handwritten notation on this telegram by Mr. Eldred D. Kuppinger, Assistant
                        Chief of the Special Division, states that these figures were checked with
                        the President’s War Relief Control Board, which indicated that they were
                        accurate and that they included contributions in kind as well as in
                        cash.</note> It states that in the first 10 months of 1943 various medical
                    supplies, clothing and foodstuffs to a value of 10¼ million dollars have been
                    shipped to the Soviet Union.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
